{"word":"ἀτάλλω","slug":"ἀτάλλω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>ἀτάλλω</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:ἀταλός'><el>ἀταλός</el></a>\n<br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b>only in <a href='S:present tense'>pres.</a> and <a href='S:imperfect tense'>imperf.</a>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>to skip in childish glee, gambol</i>, <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b>. <a href='S:active signification'><a href='S:Active voice'>Act.</a></a> <i>to bring up a child, rear, foster</i>, like <el>ἀτιτάλλω</el>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>:—<a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>Pass.</a></a> <i>to grow up, wax</i>, <b>Hhymn.</b>; the <a href='S:active signification'><a href='S:Active voice'>Act.</a></a> is so used by <b><a href='S:Hesiod'>Hes.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}